column62: Inadequate Blocking and Bracing; Inadequate Blocking and Bracing
column168: Received a call from rail representative that container ingated and was leaking.  J.B. Hunt Transport immediately called hazmat spills contractor.  Cleanup crew was contracted for remediation.  From the information received by the contractor and photos of the unit, it appears that there was improper blocking/bracing...one of the pallets used for blocking/bracing caused the outer portion of the IBC to break resulting in a puncture in the top portion of the inner IBC.  OR...the product expanded inside the IBC resulting in the top portion of the IBC to rupture and causing the outer IBC to break.  There is no way to estimate the duration of the release.  The container was ingated in TX and arrived in CA leaking.  The size of the hole was approximately the size of a pen in the upper right corner of the inner IBC.  The outer IBC was busted down the entire corner on the same side that the hole occurred.
column169: Shipper has been notified of the spill/leak.  Container was preloaded and our driver would not have been able to verify the entire contents of the container for blocking/bracing.  Also, if the result of the spill were due to the product expanding, there was nothing that our driver could have done to foresee this incident.  Possible use of superior packaging or better training on the individual product on the shipper's end might deter this incident in the future.

column168: A shipment of a chrome sludge that consisted of a liquid/solid mixture was incorreclty packaged in plastic lined flexible IBC's.  At the time the material was accepted for transportation, the driver inspected the containers and identified no evidence of leaking or damage.  The driver did, however, fail to identify that an incorrect package was selected for the transportation of a waste stream containing a liquid component.  During the course of the trip, the driver made a routine stop at Clean Harbor's 10-day in transit storage facility located in Redisville North Carolina for the purpose of consolidating a less than truckload quantity of hazardous waste onto a secodn transport vehicle for continued transportation.  Upon arrival at this location, the load was inspected and it was identified that approximatley 1 pint of liquid had escaped from the container onto the floor of the van trailer.  Facility personnel immediately absorbed the free liquids with a suitable absorbant material and initiated a response action.  This response action included the solidifcation of the liquid component of the material and repackageing the 2 IBC's into alternate package for continued transportation.  ALl clean-up debris was added to the containers and was disposed of at the intended waste management facility.  This operation was conducted without incident.
column169: In order to prevent a recurrence, the customer has been notified of the incident and has been advised that an alternate container must be used for future shipments.  In additon, we have taken appropriate actions to both re train the driver and issue disciplinary actions to educate and illustrate the serious nature of his failure to conduct a proper inspection of containers being accepted for transportation.  Finally, a review of proper package selection and inspection has taken place with all drivers associated with this business unit to ensure that all employees are aware of the incident and the corrective actions taken to preclude a repeat occurence.

column168: A cargo tank operated by Clean Harbors Environmental Services, Inc. arrived at RF Microdevices in Greensboro, NC to load a shipment of N-Methyl Pyrrolidone.  Upon arrival, the driver connected the transfer hose and placed a containment/spill pan under the connection.  As the loading operation was nearing completion, the driver noticed that a leak developed from the hose in close proximity to the point where it connected to the tank where product was being extracted from.  The driver immediately shut the pump off and closed the valves to prevent a significant release.  Before he could finish closing the valve, approximately 10 gallons of product was released to the spill containment pan and the concrete containment area where the transfer was being conducted.  The driver immediately notified the shipper and proceeded to switch out the damaged hose.  With the replacement hose in place, the driver vacuumed uu all free liquids into the tank and then spread an absorbant material on any residual liquid not able to be collected with the hose.  This material was containerized and placed into storage at the shipper's location pending shipment to a licensed waste management facility. Once the area was cleaned to the satisfaction of the shipper, the driver secured the transfer equipemnt and proceeded to the intended waste management facility.
column169: At the conclusion of the spill clean-up, the damaged hose was inspected at it was discovered that a crack measuring between 1 - 2 inches developed in the body of the hose close to the fitting.  THis crack was not visible at the time the driver connected the hose to the transfer tank.  Upon return to the driver's home dispatch location, the hose in question was disposed of and a replacement hose put in its place.  In order to orevent a recurrence, the driver was een re instructed to ensure that a thorough inspection be performed on all transfer/delivery hoses and those showing evidence of deterioration be taken out of service and replaced.  In addition, the terminal manager will be inspecting all hoses assigned to his location for the purpose of identifying any hoses that show evidence of excessive wear and/or deterioration.

column168: On 04/03/2009 at 05:15 hours, personnel in the CSXT Tampa Yard discovered GATX 6285, a loaded tank car of sulfuric acid, leaking from the liquid valve. The car was isolated and the shipper was notified via CHEMTREC (# 2009-04-03-00022). SWS, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found the liquid line valve was less than hand tight on the liquid line pipe nozzle. SWS personnel tightened the liquid valve on the liquid line pipe nozzle and the leak stopped.  The car was decontaminated and the shipper obtained a FRA movement approval (# FRA - 09040141).  The car was released to continue destination. This incident did require a special switching move.    Cause Code: 282  NARRI:  5 (5+5+0) x (2+0) = 100

column168: On April 10, 2009, transporter - Freehold Cartage delivered a shipment of PCB containing materials and other wastes to the Veolia, Port Washington WI facility. This shipment was to be transferred to a Veolia truck and sent for delivery to the Veolia, Phoenix AZ facility. Upon delivery to the Port Washington, WI facility, a small amount of an oily liquid was discovered in the secondary containment system within the trailer. Upon further inspection it was determined that the oil was from a PCB contaminated transformer (273 ppm PCB). It was also determined that less than one gallon of oil was released in the trailer. The spilled PCB contaminated oil was cleaned up and containerized for disposal. The transformer inspection also revealed that the cover on top of the transformer had not been properly secured prior to shipment. The movement of the oil within the transformer during transport caused some of the oil to spill out of the top of the transformer. Following clean up the transformer was resealed and transported to the Veolia Phoenix facility without further incident.
column169: An internal safety alert document was distributed to all Veolia ES Technical Solutions locations to be used a training tool.

column168: Upon arrival at the receiver, the load was initially refused due to seven super sacks being torn. The integrity of the packages was compromised due to the packages rubbing against the side of the inside of the container. The product never left the confines of the container. Investigation was done by the shipper and they believe that the problem lies in the pallet size rather than cardboard on the side of the container, however, the shipper has indicated that they will still put cardboard or another means to protect the load from the rivets or any other problem the walls of the container might present. Photos were taken showing that the super sacks were compromised.”
column169: The incident has been brought to the shipper’s attention. Shipper has performed an investigation and has discussed the proposed outcome with us. ShiØper believes that current blocking/bracing measures are sufficient and that changes to pallet size and added protection will eliminate any future incidents. Additional explanation is included as an attachment that Shipper has sent to Carrier. Carrier agrees with Shipper that proposed measures should eliminate the problem. Photos of the new measures have also been included. Additionally Shipper has notified Carrier that photos are taken of every load before dispatch for quality assurance measures.”  Shipper has taken great measures to insure that there will be no environmental issues. With the measures taken, we feel that future incidents will be extremely minimal. Please feel free to contact me with any questions or concerns with this amendment.

column168: File 24934 - On April 3, 2009, the dome lid on a tractor-tanker was not properly secured and allowed product to leak from the opening while traveling down the road.  Approximately 15 gallons of hydrogen peroxide product were released onto an asphalt road surface.  The Outagamie County hazmat team arrived on site and worked with state regulators to correct the situation.  The free product was neutralized to a 6.5 pH.  The liquid was then flushed from the street at the direction of Wisconsin Department of Natural Resources.

On 4//8/09 at approximately 1130 hours a Rig Classic Transportation truck was receiving a load of 7500 gallons of Methyl alcohol (methanol) at IMTT-Bayonne.  The truck had approximately 3,000 gallons of methanol loaded when the IMTT operator detected a leak from underneath the trailer compartment.  The operation was shut down and a 5-gallon pail was placed under the trailer to contain the dripping product.  The truck was moved to a secured containment area and arrangements were made to have another truck brought to the area and transfer product from the leaking trailer to the empty one.  The second trailer was then brought to the loading area and the operation resumed without further incident.  The exact cause of the leak could not be determined since it ocurred under trailer's insulation layer.
column169: IMTT-Bayonne contacted the customer of the product to inform them of the incident.  The customer subsequently contacted the transportation company and will address any mechanical or structural issues with the truck or related components to prevent recurrences.

AFTER READING THE HAZARDS AND WEARING ALL OF THE APPROPRIATE PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT, SHE PLACED THE PACKAGE IN A LINED SPILL TRAY AND TOOK IT TO THE HAZARDOUS MATERIAL DISPOSAL AREA TO BE  PROCESSED. HE ALSO NOTICED THAT THERE WAS NO HAZARDOUS MATERIAL MARKINGS OR EXEMPTIONS WRITTEN ON THE OUTER  BOX. THE RESPONDER THEN NOTIFIED HIS RMP SO THAT PICTURES COULD BE TAKEN OF THE PACKAGE AND A COPY OF THE PACKAGING LIST WAS MADE. THE DAMAGED MATERIAL WAS THEN PROCESSED THROUGH THE DMP.

column168: SRIX 83102 was noted by carrier personnel with product on sides of car.  Car isolated and shipper notified.     Shipper representatives, Hepaco, Inc., responded and replaced the defective manway cover gasket and properly tightened the manway securement bolts stopping the release.

column168: 20 foot intermodal container SUDU 196558 was noted by carrier personnel with product leaking from the container.  Contained was isolated and shipper notified.    Shipper representatives, Pettit Environmental, responded and found the container loaded with 76 metal drums of resin solution which were properly blocked and braced with no leakage or release.  Two 5 gallon pales of resin hardener had been loaded on top of the drums without and type of load securement, blocking or bracing.  The 5 gallon pales had been damaged and released almost all their contents onto the drums inside the container with some residue leaking from the container.    The 2 damaged pales of hardener were removed from the container and properly disposed of.  The remaining drums were removed, cleaned and repackaged for delivery. The container was decontaminated and the residue material properly disposed of.
column169: No additional comments.

column168: PACKAGE WAS MAKING ITS WAY DOWN THE SORT CHUTE UNDAMAGED WHEN A PAIR OF TIRES CAME DOWN AND CRUSHED THE BOX. SUPERVISOR THEN PROMPTED RESPONDER TO DON ALL SAFETY GEAR AND TO CONTAIN AND CORDON OFF THE AREA.  SPILL WAS THEN TREATED WITH SODIUM BICARBONATE TO NEUTRALIZE IT.  SPILL WAS PLACED IN A SPILL TRAY ALONG WITH BOTTLES AND BOX WHICH WAS SATURATED BY THE SODIUM HYDROXIDE.
column169: CAN NOT RECOMMEND ANY ACTIONS IN THE PROCESS TO KEEP THIS EVENT FROM REOCCURING.  IT SO HAPPENS THAT THIS INCIDENT WAS NOT CAUSED BY ANY HUMAN ERROR OR INTERVENTION.

column168: BNSF intermodal operations reported inbound intermodal container JBHU 244030 entrained on a rail flatcar as the top stacked unit was leaking an unknown substance which also leaked onto the outside of the intermodal container under it. JBHU 244030 was carefully deramped and placed within the intermodal facility's containment area. Shipper contractor's inspection of JBHU 244030 revealed a poly IBC (UN Spec 31HA1) near mid-container that had a cut at the top front corner of this IBC. Movement during transit resulted in product being expelled from the opening at this cut area. It appeared that the cut was at the edge of a depression that may have been caused by an object falling atop of this IBC. The remaining product within the compromised IBC was transferred into another suitable IBC and the spillage inside the intermodal container was cleaned. Afterwards, all lading removed was reloaded inside of the cleaned container, adjusted and blocked/braced for further transportation. The spillage on the outside of JBHU 244030 and the other impacted intermodal container was cleaned. Response was concluded by approximately 1800 hrs. PDT, 4/04/09.

column168: Unit was involved in an accident on I 81 South in the area of Woodstock, VA.  Unit subsquently caught fire due to fuel release from a passenger car and the diesel fuel on-board the unit.  It is unknown the total amount of containers damaged as a result of the crash and the number that were melted/consumed by the fire.  All of the containers became unidentifiable by the end of the event.  A contract clean up company and state environmental agencies oversaw the clean up while the local emergency response extinguished the fire.  All run off from firefighting activites were contained in a bermed area for reclaimation and disposal.      Also consumed in the crash/fire/and or packaged for disposal are the following items all from the same Ecolab, Inc. shipping location:    4 boxes Sodium Hydorxide Solid Mixture, 8, UN1823, PGII LTD QTY. 84 lbs.  6 pails Hypochlorite Solution, 8, UN1791, PGIII 1791 lbs.  1 pail Formic Acid Solution, 8, UN3412, PGII 46 lbs.  4 pails Hypochlorite Solution, 8, UN1791, PGIII 205 lbs.   4 pails Sodium Hydroxide Solution, 8 UN1824 PGII 241 lbs.  6 boxes Phosphoric Acid Solutions, 8, UN1805, PGIII  269 lbs.  2 boxes Ethanolamine Solutions, 8, UN2491, PGIII 70 lbs.  3 pails Hypochlorite Solution, 8, UN1791, PGIII 153 lbs.  3 pails Sodium Hydroxide Solution, 8 UN1824 PGII 180 Lbs.   2 boxes Corrosive Solid NOS, 8, UN1759, PGIII (Sodium Hydroxide) 78 lbs.  3 drums Hypochlorite Solution 8, UN1791, PGIII 453 lbs.  2 pails Sodium Hydroxide Solution, 8 UN1824 PGII 120 lbs.  3 boxes Hypochlorite Solution, 8, UN1791, PGIII 76 lbs.  1 boxes Sodium Hydroxide Solid Mixture, 8, UN1823, PGII LTD QTY. 21 lbs.  5 boxes Corrosive Solid NOS, 8, UN1759, PGIII (Sodium Hydroxide) 195 lbs.  1 drum Corrosive Liquid Basic Inorganic NOS, 8, Un3266 PGII (Sodium hydroxide       and Sodium Hypochlorite)561 lbs.  2 drums Corrosive Liquid Acidic Inorganic NOS 8 UN3264 PGII (Phosphoric and Nitric Acid) 1166 lbs.  2 drums Caustic Alkali Liquid NOS 8 UN1719 PGII (Sodium Hydroxide, Sodium Hypochlorite) 1182 lbs.  2 drums Sodium Hydroxide Solution 8, UN1824 PGII 1154 lbs.  3 pails Hypochlorite Solution, 8, UN1791, PGIII 153 lbs.  1 box Sodium Hydroxide Solid Mixture, 8, UN1823, PGII LTD QTY. 21 lbs.  1 box Sodium Hydroxide Solution 8, UN1824 PGII 40 lbs.  2 boxes Sodium Hydroxide Solution 8, UN1824 PGII 91 lbs.  1 box Sodium Hydroxide Solution, 8 UN1824 PGII 45 lbs.  5 boxes Corrosive Solid NOS, 8, UN1759, PGIII (Sodium Hydroxide)290 lbs.    Due to the damage done to the packages due to heat and fire, nothing was identifiable on them as far as packaging information. All bill of ladings and MSDS for products is available upon request.

column168: The RFL package was transported by Continental Airlines from Houston, Texas (IAH) to London Heathrow, England(LHR) airport by air without incident.  The package was downloaded from aircraft and transported to Ground Handler warehouse for storage  prior to subsequent road feeder journey to NewCastle, England (NCL).  The package was stored in Dangerous Goods area in good condition.  When the package was retrieved for road feeder tranport the following day, it was observed to be leaking content.  The outer package was saturated with flammable paint.  The outer package was opened for inspection which revealed the inner packages were damaged.    The inner packages consisted of two 2.5 Liter metal cans and two .5 Liter metal cans.  One 2.5 Liter can was dented in the middle portion approximately 2 inches inward. The wire handle was loose from the keeper.  One 5. Liter can was dented close to the lid which caused the lid to open.     All four cans were contained in a clear polymer bag.  It appears the wire handle punctured the polymer bag resulting in the release.    Pictures of damage are attached.

column168: Two FRA Railroad Safety/Hazardous Material Inspectors inspecting railcars in the BNSF railyard reported TJRX 30029 (DOT 111A100W1 tank car) "venting to atmosphere" via the manway closure. Later, TJRX 30029 was relocated to the repair track in the railyard for further inspection and necessary corrective action. The consignee was notified and assistance requested. The consignee responder reported finding the manway securement bolts in the proper tool tight condition. Inspection of the manway gasket revealed the gasket was split at one side which prevented a good seal that resulted in the release of vapor only from the manway closure. The responder replaced the manway gasket in kind and resecured the manway lid which eliminated any further vapor release. Response was concluded by approximately 1300 hrs. CDT, 4/07/09.   The specification stencil on TJRX 30029 indicated that the last tank qualification was completed in the year 2005.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column168: This shipment was consigned to Hawaiian Airlines C/O Delta Airlines Cargo, in Sacramento, CA. The Cargo Agent processing the outbound freight for Hawaiian Airlines subsequently placed the pallet into an ULD and loaded it on the outbound Hawaiian Airlines Flight #19.
column169: GAT Airline Ground Support has re-trained their agents in proper procedures for:  1.  Segregation of inbound and outbound shipments with special emphasis on handling and staging.  2.  HAZMAT Recognition Training.  3.  Disciplinary action of the employee involved.  4.  Lead or Supervisor will validate all ULD and/or pallets before delivery to aircraft.  5.  Local cargo management will review the existing procedures of segregation of inbound and outbound traffic, build-up process of ULD's and/or pallets for accuracy and a validation process to ensure compliance with all shipments

column168: Driver was in left hand lane of interstate after just passing another truck.  He was unable to avoid hitting a 300 lb hydraulic jack in a crate on the roadway that most likely fell off another truck.  The driver then lost control and struck a concrete barrier causing the tractor/trailer to roll on to it's side.  There was a diesel spill but only a minor product spill coming a drip from a washout cap on one of the compartments of the cargo tank. The highway was closed down for about 12 hours until the product could be safely transferred to another cargo tank.  A response vendor was called out to clean up the diesel spill and stand by during the transfer of the product.
column169: There isn't much the driver could have done to avoid this road hazard.  There were reports that a police car had hit the crate shortly before and hadn't been able to get a warning out yet.

On 04/19/09 at 17:03 hours, personnel in the CSXT Boyle Yard, Birmingham, AL, discovered SCMX 2646, a loaded tank car of Isopropanol, leaking from around the manway area of the car. The tank car was isolated and the shipper, Shell Chemical was notified thru CHEMTREC (#2009-04-19-00032). State and local officials were also notified of the incident. SWS / Eagle Environmental, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene. Upon arrival, SWS / Eagle personnel found two manway bolts were less than tool tight. The manway was opened to check the gasket; SWS representatives found that the tank car was full to within 1 inch of the top of the manway nozzle. The shipper was notified again of the problem and dispatched a truck to off load 3,000 gallons. When the transfer was completed, the car was decontaminated, sealed and sent on to destination.           NARRI :  5 (5+3+0) * (2+0) = 80  Cause Code = 200    No 7.1 required  Car was moved by CSXT crews to isolate.

column168: The driver, Irving Day, did not follow protocol in closing the vent valve on top of the Cargo Tank, which led to the scrubber tank.  Irving did not close the bleeder valve to the scrubber tank vent/release.  While the vehicle was in motion and the fluid inside the tanker was sloshing, it eventually forced fluid to the top vent line into the scrubber tank, then released fluid thru the vent valve of the scrubber onto the ground/pavement.  Called in a clean up crew to neutralize the product and clean up.
column169: I, Freddie Duhon, met with the driver Irving Day on Monday April 06, 2009 to discuss and evaluate the events that occurred in the incident.  It was determined as driver error.  We also discussed that Irving would, in the future, check to see that the vent lines/valves from the tanker and scrubber be closed before moving the vehicle from any location.

column168: UNIVAR driver picked up 6 cubic yard boxes of waste at the customer's location (Peerless Products Fort Scott KS). The UNIVAR driver did not notice anything unusual during the loading of waste onto our truck, the driver secured load for return to UNIVAR USA Inc. 220 S Barnes Springfield, MO. Upon arrival at UNIVAR at approximately 2:15 pm, the driver noticed liquid dripping from the trailer. Our driver notified company officals who notified the National Response Center along with both the Missouri and Kansas DNR. A response contractor was retained to clean up the leaking containers, UNIVAR trailer and equipment. A UNIVAR supervisor retraced the truck's route from Fort Scott KS to Springfield MO and discovered 4 locations where the material had leaked during traffic stops. The response contractor was dispatched to the 4 locations and where they cleaned the roadbed of the residual material, the locations are as follows:  1. Kansas - Intersection of Highway 69 and Highway 54 (approximately 3-4 lbs)  2. Missouri - Intersection of Highway 54 and Ash (approximately 2-3 lbs)  3. Missouri - Intersection of Highway 54 and Washington 9 approximately 2-3 lbs)  4. Missouri - Chestnut and Barnes in Springfield (approximately 2-3 lbs)  Clean up was completed by approximately 2:15 am April 9, 2009.  Our investigation has determined that the filtercake had not been completely pressed allowing liquid to accumulate on the surface of the filtercake. During transit the inside liner of the cubic yard box shifted allowing the accumulated liquid to leak from the container.
column169: Our waste specialist will review with the customer their processes on filtercake pressing and container filling. UNIVAR will review with our driving employees waste pick up and inspection procedures.

column168: FRTL was delivering gas to a customer location. While preparing to unlaod the driver hooked up his vapor recovery hose and put the fitting on the regular drop and then pulled his hose to the drop fitting, not connecting the two. The driver began to unload the fuel, pulling the lever on the head valve (but had not yet opened the belly valve). The driver immediately realized what he had done and shut the head valve off. Approximately 5-15 gallons did leak from the bottom of the hose. Driver was able to contain spill with spill pads but did call SWS First Response out to the scene. No fuel reached drains or soil. The driver with the help of terminal manager and SWS was able to clean up the spill to the satisifaction of the terminal personnel.
column169: Driver did not follow proper unloading procedures and will be required to again watch the Florida Rock & Tank Lines unloading training video. Driver will also have IPO's (incident prevention observations) conducted on him prior to returning to duty.

ON MONDAY, APRIL 13TH, 2009 AT 2:40PM, I WAS INFORMED BY ANDY VASKE OF A SPILL THAT JUST OCCURRED AT THE MESERVEY LOCATION INVOLVING THE RELEASE OF BULK N-SERVE FROM A CONTAINER ON THE BED OF A TENDER TRUCK.  APPARENTLY THE FEMAIL QUICK-COUPLER BECAME LOOSE AND FELL FROM THE MAIL QUICK-COUPLER ALLOWING PRODUCT TO FREE FLOW FROM THE BOTTOM OF THE TANK.  SINCE THE BALL VALVE WAS NOT IN THE "CLOSED" POSITION, MATERIAL WAS FREELY FLOWING ONTO THE TRUCK BED AND THEN TO THE GROUND.  THE DRIVER OF THE TRUCK, DAVID WEIDE, UNAWARE OF WHAT HAD TAKEN PLACE PULLED THE TRUCK ALONG SIDE THE OFFICE AND A FELLOW EMPLOYEE NOTICED THE MATERIAL BEING SPILLED AND QUICKLY TURNED OFF THE VALVE.  WE ESTIMATE THAT 15 GALLONS OF N-SERVE WAS LOST ON THE 3 1/2 BLOCK STRETCH OF MAIN STREET, (REFERRED TO AS 1ST STREET) AND 25 GALLON WAS LOST WHERE THE TRUCK WAS PARKED.  THE CITY OF MESERVEY SPREAD GRAVEL ON THE AFFECTED AREA (OHIO STREET TO DES MOINES STREET) AND USED A TRACTOR AND BLADE TO SPREAD THE GRAVEL EVENLY TO GET MAXIMUM ABSORPTION. FLOOR DRY AND FINE LIMSTONE WAS THEN BROUGHT IN TO HELP WITH WET SPOTS TO CLEAN THEM UP AS WELL.  IT WAS SPREAD OUT, PUSHED ABOUT WITH A BROOM AND ALLOWED TO SOAK UP WHAT LITTLE MATERIAL WAS LEFT BEHIND THE GRAVEL APPLICATION.  THE MATERIAL UNDER THE TRUCK HAD POOLED ON THE CRUSHED ROCK AND GRAVEL BASE AND A SKID STEER LOADER WAS USED TO DIG DOWN TO WHERE THE PRODUCT HAD MIGRATED, WHICH WAS ABOUT 1 FOOT.  ALL RECOVERED CONTAMINATED ROCK, GRAVEL, AND ABSORBENT MATERIAL WAS STAGED IN A CONTAINMENT PAD WHERE IT WILL BE SPREAD OVER FARM LAND.  I ARRIVED ON THE SCENE AT 4:00 PM AND THE MATERIAL WAS ALREADY REMOVED FROM WHERE THE TRUCK PARKED AND THE GRAVEL THAT WAS APPLIED TO THE STREET WAS WORKING WELL TO ABSORB THE MATERIAL AND WAS READY FOR PROPER PICKUP.  13 EMPLOYEES WITH BROOMS, SHOVELS AND A SKID STEER LOADER SWEPT THE ENTIRE WEST SIDE OF THE STREET AND RECOVERED THE MATERIAL IN A VERY ORDERLY AND METHODICAL FASHION.  THE SKID STEER LOADER WAS USED TO SCRAPE THE MATERIAL IN SMALL PILES WHERE IT WAS THEN SHOVELED INTO THE BUCKET AND PUT INTO THE RECOVERY AREA.  MERSERVEY LEADERS JON KADUCE (ALSO THE FIRE CHIEF) AND FRANK UHDE TOOK CONTROL OF THE SITUATION FROM THE BEGINNING AND DID A GOOD JOB IN CONTROLLING TRAFFIC FROM TRACKING THE MATERIAL ELSEWHERE. A FIRE DEPARTMENT PICKUP WAS STAGED AT ONE END OF THE CLEANUP ZONE AND ANOTHER FIRE DEPARTMENT VAN PARKED AT THE OTHER END OF THE SPILL AREA TO KEEP THE MINIMAL TRAFFIC SLOWED DOWN AS THEY PASSED BY FOR THE SAFETY OF THE EMPLOYEES DOING THE CLEANUP.  ON MY TRIP TO THE SCENE I ASKED THE LOCATION TO GET THE MSDS SHEETS READY FOR REVIEW AND TO HAVE THE EMERGENCY ACTION PLAN READY AS WELL SO THE VARIOUS AGENCIES COULD BE CONTACTED.  UPON MY ARRIVAL I REVIEWED THE MSDS TO MAKE SURE THE EMPLOYEES WERE NOT SUBJECT TO ADDITIONAL HAZARDS AND THAT PROPER CLEANUP PROCEDURES COULD CONTINE IF POSSIBLE. AT ABOUT 4:15 I CALLED PERS AND TALKED WITH LES ABOUT WHAT HAD TAKEN PLACE.  SINCE THIS PRODUCT WAS
column169: THE SOLUTION TO PREVENT THIS TYPE OF RELEASE IS TO FOLLOW PROCEDURE AND PROTOCOL.  EMPLOYEES ARE GIVEN YEARLY FORMAL INSTRUCTION AS WELL AS PERIODIC REMINDERS FROM THEIR SUPERVISOR ON HOW TO CONDUCT A SAFE AND EFFECTIVE DELIVERY.  IF THE EMPLOYEE CHOOSES TO IGNORE THIS INSTRUCTION THEN THE SYSTEM BEGINS TO BREAK DOWN.  THE VALVE IS IN PLACE FOR A REASON...THE CAM-LOCK IS ALSO THERE FOR A REASON, BUT IF THE TOOLS ARE NOT USED AS THEY WERE DESIGNED AND INTENDED THEN THE LEVEL OF RISK INCREASES DRAMATICALLY AND WE LEAVE OUR DESTINY UP TO FATE RATHER THAN PROPER INSTRUCTION AND PREPARATION.  WE HAVE PUT OUT A STERN MESSAGE TO THE ENTIRE MAXYIELD TEAM TO MAKE ALL TRANSPORTS SAFE.  THIS BEGINS WITH DOING A THOROUGH WALK AROUND THE VEHICLE LOOKING FOR ANY FLAGS THAT MAY CONTRIBUTE TO A FAILURE OR ACCIDENT.  THINGS TO LOOK FOR MIGHT INCLUDE LOOSE HOSES, OPEN VALVES, LOOSE LUG NUTS, LEAKAGE OF A TANK, TANKS NOT PROPERLY SECURED, PROPER PLACARDS, ITEMS ON THE DECK THAT ARE NOT SECURED WHICH COULD BLOW OFF, ALL HOSE CONNECTIONS SECURED, POWER TO A PUMP DISCONNECTED, ETC.  THESE ARE JUST SOME OF THE MANY THINGS TO LOOK FOR PRIOR TO MOVING THE VEHICLE.  FOOTNOTE:  IT'S UNFORTUNATE THAT THINGS LIKE THIS HAPPENS WHEN THE FAILURE SOURCE COMES DOWN TO AN INDIVIDUAL MAKING POOR CHOICES.  ALL THE SAFETY DEVICES IN THE WORLD WILL NOT MATTER IF WE DO NOT USE THEM.  IF WE CANNOT PROPERLY ENGAGE IN THE TASK, THEN WE SHOULD REMOVE OURSELVES FROM THE TASK ALTOGETHER BECAUSE WE BECOME AN ELEVATED RISK TO NOT ONLY OURSELVES, BUT THE PEOPLE WE WORK WITH AND THE COMPANY WE WORK FOR.  TOM WINKEL

column42: PETROLEUM DISTILLATES, N.O.S. OR PETROLEUM PRODUCTS, N.O.S.
column168: On April 16, 2009 at 19:44 hrs., personnel in the CSXT Queensgate Yard discovered NATX 38609, a loaded  tank car of Petroleum Distillates, N.O.S., leaking from the liquid line on top of the car. The car was isolated and the shipper was notified via CHEMTREC (Report # 2009-04-16-00184).   A CSXT emergency response contractor, Eagle Construction, was dispatched to the scene and found the stem of the ball valve was loose and the packing had dislodged itself from the valve. Eagle personnel replaced the gasket and the leak stopped. Eagle representatives decontaminated the valve area, cleaned up the spilled material and the car was released for transport. This incident did require a special switching move.         NARRI :  2 (5+1+0) * (2+0) = 24    Cause Code = 296
column169: No additional comments.

column168: On April 18th at 18:50 hours, personnel in the CSXT Augusta Yard discovered ACFX75301, a loaded tank car of Cyclohexane, leaking from the bottom outlet valve.  The car was isolated and Chemtrec (Report number 2009-04-18-00101) assisted in contacting DSM Chemicals to respond and investigate.  DSM representatives found that the cause of the release was due to an open top operated bottom outlet valve and the bottom outlet cap was less than tool tight.  DSM personnel properly secured the railcar and collected the one gallon of released product for recycling at their facility.  The car was then released for final destination.  An AAR QA Program, 7.1 Nonconformance Report was not completed for this incident.  Note: This incident did not require a special shipping move.    Cause Code: 148  NARRI: 5(5+3+0) X (2+0) = 80
column169: Ensure loaders follow checklist system as an effort to reduce future non-accidental releases.

column168: On April 20, 2009 at 14:48 hrs., personnel in the CSXT Queensgate Yard discovered UTLX 67088, a loaded  tank car of Sodium Hydrosulfide leaking from the top of the car. The car was isolated and the shipper was notified via CHEMTREC (Report # 2009-04-20-00165).  Eagle Construction, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found the vacuum relief device to be faulty.  Eagle personnel removed the vacuum relief device, replaced it with a plug and the leak stopped.   The car was held pending FRA movement approval.     An AAR QA Program, 7.1 Nonconformance Report was completed for this incident.  Note: This incident did require a special shipping move.    Cause Code: 461  NARRI:  2(5+3+1) x (2+0) = 36

column168: On 04/26/09 at 09:08 hours, personnel in the CSXT Russell yard, Raceland KY, discovered TILX 320102, a residue tank car last containing Petroleum Distillates, leaking from the bottom of the car. The car was isolated in the receiving yard and all CSXT employees were advised to avoid the immediate area near the rail car. The shipper was notified via CHEMTREC (Report #2009-04-26-00054). A CSXT emergency response contractor, Weavertown Environmental, was dispatched to the scene and found that the bottom outlet handle was not in the locked and pinned position. The handle was placed into the lock and pin position and properly sealed.  The secondary containment cap was taken off the bottom outlet, drained and tightened and the leak stopped.  The car was released to final destination.    This incident did not require a special switching move.     7.1 no trequired.      NARRI :  5 (4+1+0) * (2+0) = 50  Cause Code = 148

column168: On 04/21/09 at 12:28 hours, personnel in the CSXT Paintsville, KY, yard discovered TILX 400662, a loaded tank car of Carbon Dioxide refrigerated liquid, leaking from the regulating valves on the top of the car. The car was isolated and the shipper was notified via CHEMTREC (Report #2009-04-21-00122).  A CSXT emergency response contractor, Hepaco Environmental, was dispatched to the scene to make repairs. Upon arrival, Hepaco personnel slowed down the leak by reducing the pressure on the car thru the liquid and vapor lines, however, they could not stop the flow completely from the regulators. Shipper representatives transloaded 39,900 pounds of product and reduced the pressure in the rail car to 180 PSI. The leak stopped and the car was diverted back to the original point of loading in Augusta, GA.            A switch was made to isolate the car away from employees.  7.1 not required     NARRI :  5 (5+1+0) * (2+0) = 60  Cause Code = 419

column168: Industrial Chemicals, Inc. delivered an IBC containing Sodium Bisulfite Solution 40-43% to SES Industries, Inc. The driver parked in the loading/unloading area, opened the cargo door and removed the securing devices from the IBC. The SES lift truck operator drove up to the rear of the truck, lifted the IBC and backed away from the truck. As the operator lowered the IBC to the ground, the center of gravity shifted causing the rear of the lift truck to tilt forward. This movement caused the IBC to slide off the forks of the lift truck. The IBC struck the concrete surface on its side causing the outer structure to fail which resulted in a crack at the top of the inner packaging. The driver immediately pulled his truck forward allowing the lift truck operator to move in front of the IBC and lift it into an upright position which stopped the flow of material. SES personnel flushed the concrete surface with water and removed the remaining material from the IBC to prevent further spillage. The empty IBC was loaded back into the truck, secured and returned to the shipper's facility.
column169: The consignee is expected to use material handling equipment with an adequate load capacity to unload IBC's.

column168: Driver was delivering freight when he noticed that this 30 gallon poly drum was slightly leaking. The driver had the drum strapped against the wall of the cargo box neat the rear roll up door on the back of it. Apparently,unknown to the driver there was a bolt that held one of the rollers on the roll up door that was rubbing the drum while he was in transit subsequently rubbing a slight hole in the drum contributing to the unintentional release. The drum was laid on its side and repaired with drum putty and the spilled material was cleaned with sorbent material and placed into a recovery container.
column169: Drivers need to be aware of the clearances of protruding objects that could damage containers in transit. This was a very unusual event and will be the topic of a future driver/dock safety meeting to prevent future occurences.

I WAS TOLD THE VEHICULAR HEATER HAD AT ONE TIME CONTAINED SOME DIESEL FUEL AND STILL MIGHT HAVE SOME INSIDE. I THEN CONTACTED MIKE BURDICK OF THE SFO/FAA OFFICE TO REPORT THE INCIDENT AT 13:55 ON 4-27-09. HE LATER INFORMED ME THAT STEPHEN ISENBURG WOULD BE INVESTIGATING THE INCIDENT. THE PACKAGE WAS HELD PENDING HIS INSPECTION, AND THE CONSIGNEE WOULD BE CONTACTED TO PICK UP THE PACKAGE.

column168: ON 04/29/2009 TWO PACKAGES WERE REJECTED AND RETURNED TO SENDER BECAUSE THEY WERE ORMD PACKAGES GOING NEXT DAY AIR.  WHEN THE DRIVER GOT TO THE FACILITY THE NEXT DAY THE CUSTOMER REPACKED THE PACKAGE AND SENT WITH THE DRIVER.  AFTER RECEIVING THE PACKAGE AT THE LOCAL SORT YOU COULD HEAR THE AEROSOL CANS RATTLING IN THE BOX.  BECAUSE OF THE SUSPICION AND THE PACKAGE GOING NEXT DAY AIR THE AUDITOR OPENED THE PACKAGE TO CHECK THE CONTENTS AND REALIZED THAT THE CUSTOMER PUT THE SAME TWO PACKAGES THAT WERE REJECTED THE PREVIOUS DAY IN  A DIFFERENT OUTER PACK WITH NO MARKINS AT ALL AND TRIED TO SEND NEXT DAY AIR AGAIN.

column62: Loose Closure, Component, or Device; Loose Closure, Component, or Device; Derailment
column168: A BNSF train pulling out of the yard on the west lead track derailed six railcars including DBUX 302059 (DOT 111A100W1 tank car). The cause of this derailment was attributed to a broken rail (detail fracture). DBUX 302059 derailed all wheels and was leaning with the B-end facing downward towards the La Mirada Flood Control Channel that was adjacent to the track. A small amount of product leaked onto the side shell of DBUX 302059 that emanated from the valve flange connection at the liquid eduction line. Local F.D. responders placed a pool receptacle under DBUX 302059. BNSF contract responders tool tightened one of the four flange bolts approximately 1/4 to 1/2 turns to stop any further product release. At the time of securement, responders observed the spillage on the side shell was evaporating with no new product release evident. No product impacted the shallow water at the bottom of the channel. The contract responders also placed booms across the channel bottom to impede any undesired subsequent releases or debris. The contractors transferred the product within DBUX 302059 into tank trucks. The transfer was complete without incident by 1900 PDT, 4/09/09. Afterwards, DBUX 302059 was lifted from its overhanging position above the channel and rerailed.

Upon inspection, found approximately 1 gallon of material on side and top of car where 75 psi self closing Pressure Relief Device had activated and successfully reset it self.  Environmental contractor responded to clean car.

column168: This bulkhead flatcar was brought to the repair track for wheel replacement.  One of the containers was noticed leaking an oily liquid from the bottom.  The containers were placarded "spontaneously combustible" UN 4190.  The shipping papers indicated the material was environmentally hazardous waste solid, N.O.S.  Due to the discrepancy the repair shop area was evacuated until further information could be obtained.  The consignee was contacted through Chemtrec.  The consignee stated the containers held spent metal catalyst and the liquid was crude oil.  The car was set aside so the consignee could remove the leaking container.

column168: Report received that car had liquid sloshing from the top.  Inspection revealed three of eight man way bolts loose.  Seal ConocoPhillips 33931 was removed and the man way cover opened to inspect the gasket.  The gasket was in good condition.  The man way bolts were tightened and the cover sealed with Chemical Transportation Safety seal 2414.  ConocoPhillips seal 33932 was on the protective housing cover though it was not removed.

column168: The box was removed from the sort belt and placed on a concrete surface.  Subsequently, the box was found to be leaking.  The box was placed in a salvage drum.  The box was opened to reveal four 2.5L glass bottles. The bottles were seperated via a fibreboard partition.  There was no absorbent material and the cushioning material was in the form of styrofoam peanuts.  In addition there were no barrier bags to prevent a spilled material from escaping the box as required in 49CFR 173.27.  I asked the shipper, Adam Huegel, what the numbers and characters were for the second line on his UN POP marking. Adam said that the box, in this case, was reused and he did not have that information.  Hence, he could not have had the closure instructions.  Lastly, ICAO Packing Instruction 813 requires that glass inner packagings to be packed in a rigid plastic or metal intermediate packaging prior to being placed in the outer packaging.  That intermediate layer of packaging was also absent. I attempted to notify the FAA in SFO, but with no answer.  I then called the 24-hour FAA Western Region number and spoke to J.J.  I was transferred to 3700 where I left a message.  No call back yet.

column168: According to the information obtained, the following occurred.  While making a delivery to Alpha Water in Paramount, California, there was a release of approximately 150 gallons of product.  Apparently the release was the result of the customers fitting breaking where the offloading hose was connected.  Alpha Water personnel applied diatomaceous earth to contain the free liquid on the impacted asphalt surface.  The Los Angeles Fire Department responded to assess the site.  Ocean Blue Environmental Services, Inc. of Long Beach, California was dispatched to perform the cleanup.    Ocean Blue Environmental Services, Inc. recovered the contaminated diatomaceous earth and proceeded to power wash the impacted areas.  Two (2) 55-gallon drums of solid waste and approximately 500 gallons of waste water were generated as a result of this incident.  Ocean Blue Environmental Services, Inc. completed disposal of the waste generated as a result of the incident.
column169: Since the release was accidental, no plans currently exist to prevent recurrence.

column168: MPC transport was traveling north on Newtown Pike and had stopped at Newtown Court for the traffic light. The other vehicle was traveling west on Newtown Court and attempting to turn left on Newtown Pike, which is a four lane road. The other vehicle became disoriented and kept turning left until it travel back to the transport and went under the trailer on the driver's side. The other driver was cited for DUI and transported for treatment for minor injuries caused by the accident not exposure to material. The car struck the piping for number four compartment, the pipe cracked just below the internal valve but not at the shear joint, and product was released from the pipe. The driver used his spill kit to put absorbent pads out and contained the product to an area under the trailer. The internal valve held.

APC was travelling East on I-20 near Gilbert, SC when driver left the roadway and overturned in the median, resulting in the loss of cargo, which was 7504 gallons of Jet Fuel. Approximately 100 gallons of product was left in the cargo tank. Emergency crews were summoned, with SC Highway Patrol arriving first on the scene. Local Fire department, SC Department of Environmental Control, SCDOT, and Environmental contractor (A&D Environmental) crews worked to contain the spill and clean up. Because of the damage sustained in the crash to the cargo tank the duration of the leak was only minutes. Major damage to the overturn rails and manways (dome covers) because of the nature of the accident was the source of leakage.   East bound traffic was re-routed around the scene for approximately 6 hours. Over eight days of excavation, hauling contaminated dirt from the scene and bringing clean dirt back to the site, were required to mitigate the effects. Product did not reach any water, and was contained by natural berms. Excess product was vacuumed from the surface, testing was performed during the excavation to ensure full removal of product from the ground.
column169: Associated Petroleum Carriers, Inc. maintains ongoing training for prevention of these type accidents, including the unique handling characteristics of cargo tank trailers.

column168: A van trailer containing hazardous waste was parked in a fully contained transportation related facilioty while it was enroute from the point of generation to the intended waste management facility.  While stopped pending continued transportation, it was discoverd that a container within the trailer developed a pin hole leak allowing a small amount of material to leak through the trailer floor into the containment area where it mixed with rainwater that had accumulated in the concrete containment area.  Facility personnel immediately exited the area and activitated the facility emergncy reposne plan.  Representatives from the CT DEpartment of Environmental Protection were contact as was the Bristol Fire Department as is standard protocol.  Facility personnel entered the trailer after first donning appropriate personnel protective equipment and identified the leaking container.  The container was placed into a suitable salvage dsrum and the trailer floor was decontaminated.  All clean-up debris was containerd and was sent for disposal along with the original container.  In addition, the standing rainwater was collected from the containmnet area, containerized and disposed of as well.  The containment area was cleaned and upon completion, the laoding area was re opened.
column169: At the time the container was loaded, no evidence of leaking or damage was observed.  In order to prevent a recurrence, the driver and loading personnel have been re-instructed to ensure that each container is thoroughly inspected prior to acceptance and if a suspect container is identified, the appropriate action (e.g. transfer to a suitable container or placement in an approved salvage drum) is taken to precelud the unintentional relase of material from the package.

column168: A BNSF switch crew observed and reported ADMX 29117 (DOT 111A100W1 tank car) in the railyard with a slow drip of residue product from its bottom outlet area. A local BNSF mechanical/hazardous material responder was called to inspect and eliminate the product drips from ADMX 29117. The responder reported that the bottom operated bottom outlet valve handle was pinned, but the valve may not have been fully closed. The responder worked the bottom outlet's operating handle until the dripping ebbed and then re-pined it. Also, the bottom outlet closure plug was found not in a tool tight condition. The responder tool tightened the closure plug three full turns. Afterwards, all dripping ceased. Response was concluded by 2100 hrs. PDT, 4/21/09. All spillage/drippage evaporated.

column168: THE BXI, LLC DRIVER HAD LOADED HIS TRAILER WITH REFINED CHEMICAL OIL AND WAS DRIVING TOWARD THE SCALE HOUSE TO GET WEIGHED AND HAVE A BILL OF LADIMG GENERATED.  IN THE PROCESS OF DOING SO, HE NEEDED TO CROSS A SET OF THE RAILROAD TRACKS.  DUE TO THE ANGLE OF THE RAILROAD CROSSING, VISUAL OBSTRUCTIONS, AND OTHER FACTORS, THE DRIVER WAS UNABLE TO SEE A TRAIN BACKING THROUGH THE INTERSECTION.  THE OTHER MAIN FACTORS LEADING TO THIS INCIDENT WAS THE FACT THAT THERE ARE NO LIGHTS WARNING VEHICLES OF APPROACHING TRAINS, THE TRAIN WAS NO ILLUMINATED, AND THE RAILROAD DID NOT HAVE ANY PERSONNEL WALKING THE TRACKS AHEAD OF THE BECKING TRAIN.  THE IMPACT WITH THE TRAIN CAUSED THE TRACTOR AND TRAILER TO OVERTURN.  THE TANK ON THE TRAILER WAS RUPTURED AND APPROXIMATELY 1000 GALLONS OF REFINED CHEMICAL OIL WAS ABLE TO ESCAPE.  KOPPERS WHOSE PROPERTY THIS WAS ON, IMMEDIATELY CONTACTED AN ENVIRONMENTAL CONTRACTOR TO RESPOND TO THE SCENE AND HANDLE THE REMEDIATION.
column169: KOPPERS WILL NOW PROVIDE PERSONNEL TO WALK AHEAD OF THE TRUCKS TO ENSURE THE RAILROAD CAN BE SAFELY CROSSED.

column168: On Thursday April 23, 2009 we had several small spills of sulfuric acid along the transportation route between the GAC Chemical facility in Searsport and the Sappi Paper mill in Skowhegan.  It was first discovered by personnel at Sappi who found a couple of places inside their mill.  They then checked the Varney Road and Route 201 coming into their facility from Fairfield and found several spots on the above roads.  They notified the GAC truck driver, who called the GAC dispatch supervisor, who then notified Peter Goodwin, GAC Production/Safety Director.  Peter called Tom Griffin at Sappi and was informed of the situation.  From the information Peter was given, he determined there was a very good possibility there were other spills along the route the driver had taken.  Peter notified David Colter, GAC President, and the Maine State Police, who notified the Maine Department of Environmental Protection (MeDEP).  GAC had a crew travel the route taken by the driver from Searsport to Skowhegan and, with help from Sappi personnel and the GAC truck driver, was able to locate five (5) places where sulfuric acid had been spilled.  They were in the following order from Searsport to Skowhegan:    At the railroad tracks just before the I-95 ramp on Route 201 in Fairfield   At the Hinckley Market on Route 201 in Fairfield.   At the railroad tracks just before the Sappi mill entrance on Route 201 in   Skowhegan   On the Varney Road between Route 201 and the Sappi mill rear entrance.   At the Sappi mill between the security gate and the Chem Prep unloading area.  There were two (2) teams of GAC personnel sent out with soda ash, shovels, brooms and 35 gallon poly drums with covers.  All the spills on the route from Searsport to Skowhegan were neutralized with soda ash and swept up.  Sappi personnel put soda ash on all the spills except for the one at the railroad tracks on Route 201 by the I-95 ramp, which GAC personnel took care of.  GAC personnel cleaned up the soda ash on all the spills.  The spills were the result of a faulty safety valve on a sulfuric acid tanker, which allowed acid to drizzle out every time the product sloshed around in the tank.  The sloshing would have been most predominant when starting after stopping and when downshifting on hills.  The tank is 55 inches in diameter and was filled to a level of 43 inches. Product would have most likely leaked out during greatest amount of sloshing.  The spill dam around the dome holds approximately a gallon of liquid before it reaches the 1” drain holes.   Based on this information and the size of the releases observed during the clean up process, we believe no more than 5-10 gallons were spilled.
column169: Upon inspection of the safety valve at the GAC plant after the incident, the vacuum breaker part of the safety valve had come apart and the vacuum breaker disc had fallen into the tanker.  Inspection showed that the parts holding the vacuum breaker together had become corroded, allowing a pin to fall out, which in turn allowed a disc to unscrew and eventually come apart.  The safety valve had been pressure tested on March 16, 2009, during a quarterly inspection, and was found to be working properly.    As a corrective action, GAC Chemcial will immediately remove, disassemble, and inspect all the internal parts of the safety valves on all our sulfuric acid tankers.  We will implement a program to perform this inspection procedure on a semi-annual basis.

column168: A visual roll-by inspection of a BNSF westbound train traveling on the main track resulted in the train crew being notified that entrained SRIX 80246 (DOT 111A100W1 tank car) had leaked product on its side shell. The train crew stopped this train for closer inspection of SRIX 80246 by the train crew. The train's conductor visually inspected SRIX 80246 and reported that the spillage on the side shell appeared to be spillage deposited from the loading process since no active leak and no ground impact from the spillage was observed. The train then proceeded to the next terminal (Omaha, NE) were local BNSF operating personnel were alerted of this incident. The BNSF Assistant Director Hazardous Material whom was in Omaha was notified and inspected SRIX 80246 in detail. This BNSF responder reported finding one of eight manway securement bolts less than tool tight which prevented a good manway closure seal. The now cooled spillage atop this tank car and down the side shell emanated from the manway closure. The loose manway securement bolt was tool tightened. All other valves and fittings were inspected and found secure. Seal numbered T88448598 was removed for valve inspection, but no replacement seal was readily available to the responder. Response was concluded by 1950 hrs. CDT, 4/28/09.  SRIX 80246's side specification stencil indicated that the last tank qualification was completed in the year 2008 and next due in 2018.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column168: Tank Car GATX 5970 was discovered to be leaking by a carman performing routine inspections in the PTRA Manchester yard at approximately 1635 hours. He notified the appropriate personnel and we responded to the incident at 1705 where we found sulfuric acid dripping down the side of the tank to the ground from the two inch discharge line on top of the car. The track was secured and M&M Protection services was called to secure the leak and clean up the product on the ground. M&M arrived on scene at 1800 hrs. They released the pressure on the car and stopped the leak at 1830 at which time they began to neutralize the sulfuric acid. The cause of the leak was a cracked cap on the discharge pipe. It appears to be from wear and deterioration of the cap. THe crack ran from top to bottom on the cap, approx. three inches. Product was released account of the pressure increase in the car from the heat of the day. It was approximately 93 degrees and sunny.  The pressure forced product into the discharge pipe and through the crack in the cap. Estimated loss of product was five to ten gallons. M&M spread eight bags of soda ash on the ground to begin neutralizing the acid. They then pressure washed the car using a sodium bicarbonate solution. After cleaning the car they applied the sodium bicarbonate solution to the ground to completely neutralize the acid.  Cleanup was completed at approximately 2045.  The consignee, Shrieve Chemical in The Woodlands, TX, was notified as was the Care of Party, Agrifos located in Pasadena, TX, both parties agreed to inspect other cars of the same type for similar wear and deterioration of the discharge pipe cap.  FRA Inspector Doug Johnson was notified of the incident at approximately 1730 hrs.
column169: As stated in Part VI the consignee and care of party were taking action to inspect the cars for similar wear issues.

column168: ABOUT 2:30PM ON 4/14/09 - DRIVER LOADED AND LEFT EAST DUBUQUE REINTECH TERMINAL.  DRIVER WAS DISPATCHED TO DELONGS, SHARON, WI.  DRIVER TRAVELED RT 20 EB TO I1 RT 84 NB - WI 80 NB.  AS THE DRIVER APPROACHED THE JCT. OF 80 & 11 IN WI, HE HEARD AN AIR HISSING NOISE AND PULLED OVER AT THE JCT OF 80& 11.  AT THIS TIME THE DRIVER REALIZED HE HAD A SMALL LEAK AT THE REAR POP OFF OF HIS TRAILER.  THE DRIVER CONTACTED RONALD SCHOFF IMMEDIATELY.  AS WE WERE ASSESSING THE PROBLEM, THE HAZEL GREEN FIRE DEPARTMENT ARRIVED WITH A FIRE TRUCK.  THE FIRE TRUCK WAS DISPATCHED BY A BUS DRIVER WHO WAS FOLLOWING THE TRANSORT AND NOTICED AN ODOR.  THE BUS DRIVER WAS ALSO THE HAZEL GREEN FIRE CHIEF.  THE FIRST RESPONDER AND THE DRIVER AND I DECIDED TO GET AN EMPTY TRANSPORT AND EMPTY ONE INTO THE OTHER.  WE MADE THIS DECISION FEELING IT WAS A SAFE WIDE OPEN AREA,  THE WIMD WAS FAVORABLE, AND THIS WOULD BE SAFER THAN MOVING THE LOADED TRANSPORT. TRANSFER TOOK ABOUT 1 HOUR.  AFTER TRANSFERRING LIQUID OFF THE POP OFF RE SEALED.  ALL PARTIES ASSESSED AND FELT IT WAS SAFE TO MOVE THE TRANSPORT TO EAST DUBUQUE REINTECH FOR A COMPLETE WATER-VAPOR BLOWDOWN.  THIS TOOK PLACE BETWEEN 7:20PM ONN 4/14/09 TO 1:00AM ON THE 15TH.  TRANSPORT WAS THEN MOVED TO ALBANY, IL TO THE GM TECH CENTER.

column169: BETTER SECUREMENT OF CAP, BUNGS OR LIDS ON TOTES. DISCUSS WITH THE SHIPPER ON THE IMPORTANCE OF MAKING SURE PACKAGING OF PAILS, DRUMS,.TOTES OR MISCELLANEOUS CONTAINING HAZARDOUS MATERIALS, CHEMICALS AND LIQUID MUST BE SAFE FOR TRANSPORTING AND TRAVELING. THE SEAMS ON THE PACKAGING MUST BE ABLE TO HOLD LIQUID WITHOUT LEAKING OUT. THE DURABILITY OF A DRUM, PAIL, BAGS AND, OR TOTE MUST BE ABLE MAINTAIN THE LIQUIDS OR POWDERS TO PREVENT PACKAGE DETERIORATION. IMPORTANT THAT LIDS AND TOPS OF PACKAGES ARE SECURED AND TIGHTENED BEFORE ALLOWING TOMOVE. TOTES AND DRUMS WITH VALVES MUST BE SAFELY CLOSED AND THE CONTAINER, PAGKAGING, MUST BE DURABLE TO ENSURE NO LIQUID OR POWDER IS ALLOWED TO BE RELEASED. DISCUSS WITH SHIPPER ON PROPER, SAFE AND RELIABLE PACKAGING TO PREVENT-EASY RELEASE OF PRODUCT. PACKAGING OF CHEMICALS, HAZARDOUS MATERIALS AND LIQUIDS MUST BE THOROUGHLY INSPECTED BEFORE IT LEAVES ORIGIN!

column168: A 330 GAL DOT IBC WITH 250 GAL OF 50% SODIUM HYDROXIDE SOLUTION (CAUSTIC SODA) CRACKED LEAVING THE WILSON, NC SANDOZ SITE.  THE TRUCK HAD TRAVERSED A "SPEED BUMP" WHEN A SIGNIFICANT PORTION OF THE LIQUID LEAKED FROM THE TRUCK AND CONTINUED FOR MANY MILES IN NOTICEABLE AMOUNT AS IT DRIED ON THE ROAD SURFACE.  LOCAL FIRE DEPT., COUNTY EMERGENCY MGT., NC DOT, AS WELL AS WATER GUARD INC. PERSONNEL RESPONDED WHEN NOTIFIED SEVERAL HOURS AFTER THE INITIAL RELEASE.  SODIUM BICARBONATE DRY AND IN SOLUTION WAS APPLIED TO NEUTRALIZED THE PRODUCT.  THE NC DOT USED A SPRAY TRUCK TO TREAT THE ROADWAY.  THE EMERGENCY PERSONNEL CLOSED US 264 AT THE INTERSECTION WITH MERCK DRIVE FOR SEVERAL HOURS.  EXAMINATION OF THE IBC REVEALED A CRACK ABOVE THE VALVE IN THE TANK BODY.  THE IBC WAS WITHIN ITS INSPECTION/TEST CYCEL AND DUE FOR TEST IN AUG 2009.  ADDITIONAL CLEANUP OF THE SANDOZ SITE WAS COMPLETED 04/23/2009.    FAILURE MODES AND FACTORS  IMMEDIATE CAUSE WAS A 27-INCH CRACK WITH A 1/4 INCH SEPARATION IN THE AREA BETWEEN TWO BASE ATTACHMENT POINTS AND AN AREA 4-6 INCHES ABOVE THE OUTLET VALVE.  THE BASE HAD SOME SIGNIFICANT FORKLIFT DAMAGE FROM USE AND APPARENTLY ALLOWED THE VALVE SUPPORT AREA TO FLEX WITHOUT SUPPORT.  THE SUDDEN ACCELERATION AND STRESS OF THE IBC AT THE SPEED BUMP EXCEEDED THE ELASTIC STRENGTH.  ADDITIONAL ISSUES MAY INCLUDE ABSENCE OF A VACUUM BREAK, INCREASED BRITTLENESS WITH CONCENTRATED CAUSTIC AMD OTHERS NOT RECOGNIZED TO DATE.  INSPECTION INDICATES NO OTHER PARTIAL CRACKS INSIDE THE TANK.
column169: RECOMMENDATIONS  1) INSPECTIONS AND REPLACEMENTS OF ANY FORKLIFT DAMAGED BASE UNITS ON IBC'S PARTICULARLY THE SNYDER STANDARD TYPE INVOLVED IN THIS INCIDENT.  2) INSTRUCT LOAD PERSONNEL TO PLACE IBC'S AS FAR FORWARD AS POSSIBLE TO MINIMIZE THE SLOSH ASSOCIATED WITH PARTIAL IBC'S IN THE REAR OF THE TRUCK.  3) REVIEW EMERGENCY PLAN AND CONTACTS FOR OFF-SITE INCIDENTS.    NOTE:  FINAL DOT REPORTING AWAITS DAMAGE COST ESTIMATES AMD ANY ADDITIONAL INSPECTION RESULTS.

column168: At approximately 14:00 on 24 April 2009, after completing corrosion injection at PS# 10 the corrosion injection vehicle was in the process of entering the gate at DRB/PS# 9, when the Security guard noticed product leaking from the vehicle (Alyeska #3578). The vehicle was stopped and the support crew already at DRB/PS#9 was notified by security of the incident.  Upon the support crews' arrival at the vehicle, they noticed fluid leaking (Cortron RU-248) from numerous locations on the truck.  The security guard and one of the crew immediately started to place absorbentpads and containment. A hazard assessment was completed. Once initial notifications were made through the Alyeska Operations Control Center the area was secured, LEL readings were taken and initial clean-up was initiated.  4/24/2009: Immediate clean-up was accomplished by placing secondary containment under the vehicle at the leak points and absorbent pads were placed in and around the vehicle.  A VAC truck was used to collect the contained product.  Once the spill stopped leaking from the truck the containment was removed and the truck was towed on site and placed inside secondary containment.  4/25/2009: CASI Safety and crew started the initial investigation of the incident.  The tank was found to be empty.  A visual inspection of the valves indicated that they were closed at the time of the inspection. 999
column169: The incident investigation is ongoing.Work procedures are being reviewed for adequacy and being re-written where necessary to include all critical tasks associated with the operation, including truck operation and transport.  A checklist detailing shutdown and transportation configuration of the valves is being developed.  Locking devices on the existing cam-locks will be provided.  Management will ensure any new employee assignments for these tasks are up to date with training and qualified to perform the associated tasks.

THE DRIVER STATED THAT A CAR PASSED HIS TRUCK ON A DOUBLE YELLOW LINE WHICH CAUSED HIM TO TAKE HIS EYE OFF THE ROAD FOR A MOMENT.  WHEN THIS OCCURRED THE BACK TIRE GOT OFF THE ROAD AND HE TRIED TO EASE BACK ON THE ROAD, BUT IT HAD ALREADY STARTED TO SKID AND HE COULD NOT STRAIGHTEN BACK UP.  THEN THE TRUCK ROLLED OVER AND CAME TO A REST ON THE OTHER SIDE OF THR ROAD, THE CAB OF THE TRUCK AND THE TANK WERE DETACHED AND LAYING PARALLEL FROM EACH OTHER.  WHEN THE TRUCK ROLLED OVER THE FRONT DOME LID CAME OPEN AND THE PRODUCT IN THAT COMPARTMENT CAME OUT, BUT THE LINES UNDER THE TRUCK WERE ALSO TORN APART AND THE PRODUCT FROM THE OTHER TWO COMPARTMENTS CAME OUT LEAVING ABOUT 50 GALLONS IN EACH COMPARTMENT.  WE ARE NOT SURE HOW LONG THE RELEASE OCCURRED.  THE LOCAL FIRE DEPARTMENT WAS DISPATCHED OUT TO THE SITE ALONG WITH THE HAZMAT TEAM THAT COLUMBUS COUNTY USES.  WE DISPATCHED OUT A TEAM TO BE AT THE SITE ALONG WITH OUR ENVIRONMENTAL COMPANY TO HELP US CLEAN UP THE SITE.  THE NORTH CAROLINA DEPARTMENT OF ENVIRONMENTAL AND NATURAL RESOURCES AND EPA WERE NOTIFIED OF THE SPILL.  AT THE SITE BOOMS AND SPILL PADS WERE PLACED IN THE DITCH TO KEEP THE PRODUCT FROM MIGRATING.  A VACUUM TRUCK WAS USED TO GET THE PRODUCT OUT OF THE DITCH.  THEN DIRT WAS REMOVED FROM THE DITCH AND REPLACED WITH NEW DIRT.  GRASS SEED WAS SPREAD OUT OVER THE SHOULDER OF THE ROAD ONCE THE NEW DIRT WAS IN PLACE.  WE LEFT BOOMS OUT IN THE DITCH TO MAKE SURE THAT IF THERE WAS ANY TRACE OF PRODUCT IF WOULD NOT GO PAST THE BOOMS.  AFTER CHECKING THE BOOMS FOR A FEW WEEKS THERE WAS NO TRACE OF PRODUCT LEFT IN THE DITCH. WE RECEIVED A NOTICE OF NO FURTHER ACTION FROM NORTH CAROLINA DEPARTMENT OF ENVIRONMENT AND NATURAL RESOURCES.
column169: AFTER THE ACCIDENT OCCURRED WE MET WITH THE DRIVERS AND DISCUSSED WHAT HAPPENED AND HOW WE COULD PREVENT IT FROM HAPPENING AGAIN.  WE CONTINUE TO HAVE ON GOING TRAINING/SAFETY MEETINGS WITH OUR DRIVERS ON THE DIFFERENT DISTRACTIONOS, ROAD HAZARDS AND TRUCK ROLL OVERS.

column168: DRIVER WAS UNLOADING TRAILER 267307.  ON THE REAR OF THE TRAILER WERE SKIDS THAT WERE VERY TIGHTLY LOADED AND WEDGED TOGETHER.  THERE WERE 6 BOXES LOADED ON TOP OF A SHRINKWRAPPED SKID BUT THE BOXES ON TOP OF THE SKID WERE NOT SECURED AND THE LABELS WERE NOT FACING OUT WHERE THE DRIVER COULD SEE WHAT THE PRODUCT WAS.  AS HE WENT TO THE BACK OF THE TRAILER WITH THE SKID AND THE BOXES ON TOP, 4 BOXES FELL TO THE GROUND AND BROKE.  THE SUPERVISOR CAME OVER TO INSPECT BECAUSE THE FREIGHT WAS NOT MANIFESTED ON THE TRAILER AND THERE WAS NO INDICATION THAT THERE WAS POISON ON THE TRAILER.  AFTER THE BOXES FELL AND BROKE IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THIS WAS POISON.  THE SUPERVISOR WAS GETTING THE INFORMATION TO CALL HAZ MAT ONE WHEN SHE STARTED TO FEEL THE EFFECTS AND EVACUATED THE BUILDING.
column169: CORRECTIVE ACTION WAS TAKEN AGAINST THE LOADING TERMINAL.

column168: FLOW POLYMERS, INC. RECEIVES ASPHALT IN RAILCARS, WHICH MUST BE HEATED ABOVE 300 DEGREES F IN ORDER TO BE UNLOADED.  DURING TRANSPORTATION, THE RAILCAR COOLS OFF AND THE MATERIAL CHANGES BACK INTO ITS SOLID STATE.  A RAILCAR, TLDX 223081, WAS SHIPPED TO FLOW POLYMERS, INC. BY CSX FROM NAVAJO REFINING COMPANY IN ARTESIA, NM.  THE CAR GAD RAN ON HEAT FOR SEVERAL DAYS TO PREPARE FOR TRANSFER OF CONTENTS INTO ABOVE-GROUND STORAGE TANKS.  AROUND 0800 ON APRIL 29, 2009 THE MATERIAL WAS READY FOR THE TRANSFER.  THE SUPERVISOR VISIBLY CONFIRMED THAT THE CAR BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE (BOV) WAS IN THE CLOSED POSITION AND THE CAR SEAL WAS IN PLACE.  THE SUPERVISOR MOVED THE TRANSFER HOSE INTO PLACE TO HOOK UP. HE REMOVED THE CAP FROM THE UNLOADING PIPE.  A SLUDGE OF MATERIAL QUICKLY CAME OUT THE BOV. THEN THE CAR'S CONTENTS STARTED TO FLOW OUT OF THE CAR WITHOUT BEING ABLE TO CONNECT THE HOSE.  THE SUPERVISOR JUMPED BACK AND MADE NOTIFICATIONS.  THE BOV HANDLE WAS STILL IN THE CLOSED POSITION WITH THE SEAL IN PLACE.    BETWEEN 0810 TIL 0935, RESPONSE PERSONNEL FROM THE PLANT MOBILIZED OUT TO THE SITE AND STARTED TO BUILD CONTAINMENT DIKES OUT OF BAGS OF OIL DRY AND CONCRETE.  THE LIQUID ASPHALT MATERIAL FLOWED AROUND THE INITIAL DIKES ON FLOW POLYMERS, INC. (FPI) LEASED PROPERTY.  PERSONNEL MOVED FURTHER DOWN ONTO CSX PROPERTY TO BUILD OTHER DIKES TO CONTAIN THE FLOW IN ORDER TO PREVENT MATERIAL FROM FLOWING INTO NINE MILE CREEK.  OTHER PERSONNEL WORKED ON THE RAILCAR AND BOV.  THE WERE UNABLE TO CLOSE THE BOV FROM UNDER THE CAR.  THEY OPENED THE TOP HATCH AND ATTEMPTED JAMMING MATERIAL INTO THE VALVE FROM THE TOP TO STOP THE FLOW OF MATERIAL.  THE RAILCAR EMPTIED OUT.  APPROXIMATELY 3% OF THE VOLUME OF RAILCAR REACHED THE CREEK.  THE MATERIAL WAS ALLOWED TO HARDEN.  CSX CAME OUT.  EXTERNAL RESPONSE GROUPS (CHEMTRON CORPORATION AND SUNPRO) WERE CALLED FOR ASSISTANCE.  EXTERNAL MODIFICATIONS MADE TO NRC AND LOCAL OFFICIALS.  SEE SUNPRO REPORT # NC201364 FOR FURTHER DETAILS ON THEIR RESPONSE ACTIVITIES.
column169: The valve was installed improperly.  Personnel made aware of the issue.  Mr. Anthony Schneider (anthony.schneider@dot.gov) and Mr. Jeffrey Moore Geffrey.moore@dot.gov) from U.S. Department of Transportation, Federal Railroad Administration came out to visit the plant and the railcar.  The railcar was sealed by them for further investigation.

column168: At approximately 1300 on April 1st, 2009, a fleet service clerk brought a suitcase in to the bag room supervisor's office as he noticed strong fumes / vapors emitting from the suitcase. The supervisor (who is trained in spill response) donned PPE and opened the suitcase to investigate.  Inside she found several dental items including an empty 1 quart container of Sledgehammer Self-Cure Dental Acrylic Monomer.  The supervisor closed up the bag and moved it outside of her office as she was starting to get a headache from the fumes.      The supervisor contacted the Lead Environmental Coordinator for the station, Kim Galvin (myself).  I was able to retrieve an MSDS for the product from the manufacturer and determined the substance to be a hazardous material, flammable liquid, n.o.s., UN 1993.  The substance had not been declared or transported appropriately as a hazardous material.      The suitcase was wrapped in a plastic garbage bag to prevent release of the fumes to the employees working in the area.  It was then transported to our hazardous waste storage area.    I completed a hazardous materials report / notification to the FAA.  I then contacted FAA Hazardous Materials Specialist Christopher G. Zawarus at the Chicago Security Field Office.  Inspector Zawarus came out on April 8th, 2009 to view the material.  There were several items inside the bag...all related to dental practice...and all appeared to have been used.      We are unable to determine how much of the product may have been in the 1 quart container, however, the blanket and towels inside the suitcase were damp.  The outside of the suitcase was not, therefore it was determined that there was no release outside of the suitcase, other than the vapors emitting from the product.      The bag was checked in CLT, travelling through ORD on the way to final destination of MSP.    The passenger will be driving to ORD to pick up the bag in the near future.
column169: Better education to the passenger is needed to ensure he does not check undeclared hazardous material in the future.  AA has several checks in place to attempt to educate our passengers as well as several "triggers" that cause our ticket agents to ask questions to passengers when travelling to help identify if they are travelling with hazardous items.    Better education to our TSA or screening personnel to ensure they identify items that should not fly in passenger baggage.
